# Architecture

Follow `PLAN.md` and `STRUCTURE.md`. Do not invent parallel abstractions.

## Module responsibilities

| Location | Owns | Must not |
|---|---|---|
| `adaptron/core/agent.py` | `Agent`, type inference | Know frameworks |
| `adaptron/core/pipeline.py` | `>>`, flatten, `run()`, construction-time resolve | Call LLM APIs |
| `adaptron/core/adapters.py` | Registry + exact-pair lookup | Import third-party types |
| `adaptron/core/logging.py` | stdlib verbose stage logs | Depend on extras |
| `adaptron/core/errors.py` | `AdaptronError` hierarchy | Swallow failures |
| `adaptron/bridges/*` | `can_wrap` / `adapt` for one framework | Leak imports into core |

Prefer composition over inheritance. Keep stages loosely coupled; extend via adapters/bridges, not by editing pipeline internals for each new framework.

## Never bypass the adapter system

- Type conversion between agents happens only via registered adapters inserted at construction.
- Do not hard-code conversions inside `Pipeline.run()` or inside a bridge’s `__call__` for cross-agent handoffs.
- Do not add “helpful” automatic coercion beyond exact registry lookup.

## `wrap()` detection order (correctness-critical)

Probe **most specific → least specific**. First match wins:

1. LangChain bridge (if importable)
2. CrewAI bridge (if importable)
3. Plain-Python callable (catch-all)

Why: framework objects are also callables. If plain-Python runs first, bridges never win and agents are mis-wrapped.

## Pipeline rules

- `a >> b >> c` flattens to one `Pipeline`, never nested pipelines.
- `Pipeline` exposes `.input_type` / `.output_type` from first/last stage (composable like `Agent`).
- Execution is synchronous, single-process, linear. Preserve stage order; thread output → next input.
- Log every agent and adapter stage when `verbose=True`.

## Type inference priority

1. Explicit types passed to `wrap()`
2. `typing.get_type_hints` on the callable
3. `typing.Any` (skip adapter matching for that port)
